department_narrative: [{"editDate": "10/10/2024", "editTime": "00:22:48", "editUser": "Timothy H Ward", "narrative": "Engine 4, Battalion 1 and engine 3 were dispatched on a trailer on fire on 65 north bound. On arrival a enclosed trailer was found to be fully involved. The owner operator had detached the pickup truck from the trailer and moved it away when he realized it was on fire. Engine 4 pulled a front bumper line and began attempting to extinguish the fire, Engine 1 arrived and began removing the property from the trailer and also took a k12 saw and began opening up the side. Engine 3 reserve was dispatched for water supply. Engine 3 reserve off loaded water to engine 4 3 times, before the fire was finally extinguished. After extinguishing the fire, engine 4 and engine 1's crew continued removing the wood cabinet parts from the trailer and knocking down hot spots until no more visible. Engine 4 used the batch mix foam method to foam all the smoldering remaining areas.  After it was determined that all the fire was out, the scene was than turned over too law enforcement. "}]

department_narrative: [{"editDate": "11/05/2024", "editTime": "23:43:19", "editUser": "Joseph T Harbarger", "narrative": "Battalion one and Engine four responded to reports of a vehicle fire. Upon arrival, Battalion one reports an electric vehicle smoking with its batteries on fire. Battalion one advises Engine four to don all PPE and get ready to deploy an electric vehicle fire blanket. After the first blanket did not contain the fire, Battalion one requested Battalion two for their blanket. Pro-tow advised crews that they could not tow the vehicle due to fire hazards. Battalion one requested Engine three for scene lighting, additional water, and to use their pre-connect. Hoover Police Department shut down all lanes of the interstate because crews decided to let the fire burn out without exposures. The blankets were removed, and crews allowed the vehicle to burn down to the point where it was able to be extinguished safely. The yellow pre-connect was pulled off of Engine three, and the fire was extinguished with 1,000 gallons of water. Battalion one then requested Engine one for additional water if needed. Engine one filled Engine four's tank then returned in service. Pro-tow successfully loaded the vehicle and relocated it to their yard."}]

department_narrative:
[{"editDate": "11/13/2024", "editTime": "21:18:07", "editUser": "Geoffrey R Moore", "narrative": "Units responded to a structure fire at address listed. On E4 arrival light smoke coming from the eave on the Delta side of the structure.E4 hand laid supply line to apparatus. E4 went on an offensive attack, pulling a red 1 3/4" line through the Alpha door. Advanced the line upstairs locating the fire in a bedroom. E4 crew extinguished the fire and search for extension. Fan was placed on the Alpha side to assist with ventilation. 
R4 crew performed primary search of the fire floor. After search was complete, R4 crew assisted with searching for fire extension. 
E2 crew pulled secondary 1 3/4" line and stretched it to fire floor. Fire was out prior to charging the line. E2 crew assisted with searching for fire extension. 
Q7 searched neighboring apartment and reported all clear.
E3 crew was assigned to RIT.
Fire marshal and fire inspector arrived on scene to investigate the cause and origin of the fire.
Scene turned over to home owner."}]

department_narrative:
[{"editDate": "10/25/2024", "editTime": "20:44:40", "editUser": "Robert B Smith", "narrative": "Quint 11 responded to investigate reports of a water main break. Upon arrival, Quint 11 identified a break in the water line in front of an apartment building, which resulted in a reduction of pressure in the fire suppression system to below acceptable levels. Quint 11 contacted Birmingham Water Works at the request of building maintenance.
On-site maintenance and plumbing crews indicated they were unable to shut off the water to the affected building due to a separate fire suppression system line not being connected to the same main as the standard water supply line. Maintenance personnel requested that either the fire department or Birmingham Water Works shut off the main line at the John Hawkins Parkway vault to facilitate repairs to the suppression line.
Quint 11 advised the maintenance crew that shutting off the main line at that location would result in a complete water outage for the entire complex, necessitating the implementation of a live fire watch. Quint 11 then informed Battalion 1 of the situation, who subsequently contacted the Fire Prevention Division to relay the incident details.
Battalion 1 directed Quint 11 to communicate to maintenance that this matter did not fall under the fire department's jurisdiction and that the fire department would not be able to shut off the water to the complex. In response, building maintenance indicated they would request Birmingham Water Works to shut off the water supply. Quint 11 then informed maintenance that if Birmingham Water Works proceeded with the shutdown, they would need to notify the City of Hoover Fire Department of the situation.
Quint 11 then returned to service."}]
